{{Other uses|Seine (disambiguation)}} {{multiple image | align = right | width = 220 | direction = vertical | image1 = Seining for wild fish.jpg | alt1 = | caption1 = <center>Seining for fish in a river</center> | image2 = Seine (PSF).png | alt2 = | caption2 = <center>A basic seine net</center> }}
'''Seine '''({{IPAc-en|s|eɪ|n}} {{respell|SAYN|'}})''' fishing''' (or seine-haul fishing) is a method of [[fishing]] that employs a [[fishing net]] called a seine, that hangs vertically in the water with its bottom edge held down by weights and its top edge buoyed by floats. Seine nets can be deployed from the shore as a beach seine, or from a boat.
Boats deploying seine nets are known as [[Fishing vessel#Seiners|seiners]]. Two main types of seine net are deployed from seiners: ''purse seines'' and ''Danish seines''.
==Etymology== The word ''seine'' has origins in the Old French ''seigne'', the Latin ''sagena'', and the Greek σαγήνη ''sagēnē'' (a draw-net).<ref>[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] (1926) 13th edition, volume 23, page 587.</ref>
==History== Seines have been used widely in the past, including by [[stone age]] societies. For example, the [[Māori people|Māori]] used large canoes to deploy seine nets which could be over a kilometer long. The nets were woven from green flax, with stone weights and light wood or gourd floats, and could require hundreds of men to haul.<ref>Meredith, Paul [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/te-hi-ika-maori-fishing/2 "Te hī ika – Māori fishing"] ''Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand''. Updated 2 March 2009.</ref>
[[File:Fishermen horse seining for salmon on the Columbia River, nd (COBB 99).jpeg|thumb|Haul seining with horses on the [[Columbia River]], undated photo by [[John Nathan Cobb]]]] Native Americans on the [[Columbia River]] wove seine nets from spruce root fibers or wild grass, again using stones as weights. For floats they used sticks made of cedar which moved in a way which frightened the fish and helped keep them together.<ref name=Smith>Smith, Courtland L [http://www.oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/seine_fishing/ Seine fishing] ''Oregon Encyclopedia''. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref>
Seine nets are also well documented in [[History of the Mediterranean region|ancient cultures in the Mediterranean region]]. They appear in [[Art of ancient Egypt|Egyptian tomb paintings]] from 3000 BC. In ancient Roman literature, the poet [[Ovid]] makes many references to seine nets, including the use of cork [[Fishing net#Floats|floats]] and lead weights.<ref>Radcliffe W (1926) [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/118679# ''Fishing from the Earliest Times''] John Murray, London.</ref><ref name=Johnson1999>Johnson WM and Lavigne DM (1999) [https://web.archive.org/web/20120124152238/http://www.monachus-guardian.org/library/mededelingen35_2008a.pdf ''Monk Seals in Antiquity''] Fisheries, pp. 48–54. Netherlands Commission for International Nature Protection.</ref><ref>Gilroy, Clinton G (1845) [http://www.ebooksread.com/authors-eng/clinton-g-gilroy/the-history-of-silk-cotton-linen-wool-and-other-fibrous-substances-includin-rli/page-44-the-history-of-silk-cotton-linen-wool-and-other-fibrous-substances-includin-rli.shtml "The history of silk, cotton, linen, wool, and other fibrous substances: including observations on spinning, dyeing and weaving"] pp. 455–464. Harper & Brothers, Harvard University.</ref>
==Purse seine== {{multiple image | align = right | width = 220 | direction = vertical | image1 = Salmon purse seining.jpg | alt1 = | caption1 = <center>Fish swimming near the surface are surrounded by a wall of netting supported by floats.</center> | image2 = Salmon purse seining drawing 1.png | alt2 = | caption2 = <center>The net is drawn or "pursed" so it is closed at the bottom as well.</center> }}
A common type of seine is a purse seine, named such because along the bottom are a number of rings. A line (referred to as a purse-line) passes through all the rings, and when pulled, draws the rings close to one another, preventing the fish from "sounding", or swimming down to escape the net. This operation is similar to a traditional style purse, which has a drawstring. The purse seine is a preferred technique for capturing fish species which [[Shoaling and schooling|school]], or aggregate, close to the surface: [[sardine]]s, [[mackerel]], [[anchovies]], [[herring]], and certain species of [[tuna]] (schooling); and [[salmon]] soon before they swim up rivers and streams to spawn (aggregation). Boats equipped with purse seines are called [[Factory ship#Purse seiner|purse seiners]].
[[File:Purse seining boat, location unknown, nd (COBB 314).jpeg|thumb|Purse seiner on the U.S. Pacific Coast, photo by [[John Nathan Cobb]]]] Purse seine fishing can be a relatively [[Sustainable fishery|sustainable]] [?] way of fishing, as it can result in smaller amounts of by-catch (unintentionally caught fish), especially when used to catch large species of fish (like herring or mackerel) that [[Shoaling and schooling|shoal]] tightly together.<ref name = "gp">[http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/blog/oceans/purse-seining-when-fishing-methods-go-bad-20100518 Purse-seining: when fishing methods go bad], Greenpeace, 18 May 2010</ref> When used to catch fish that shoal together with other species, or when used in parallel with [[fish aggregating device]]s, the percentage of by-catch greatly increases.<ref name = "gp" />
Use of purse seines is regulated by many countries. In Sri Lanka, using this type of net within 7 kilometers of the shore is illegal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka fisheries authorities and navy to act against local fishermen using illegal fishing methods|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_13B/Oct21_1382334068JV.php|newspaper=Colombopage|date=21 Oct 2013}}</ref> However, they can be used in the deep sea, after obtaining permission from authorities. Purse seine fishing can have negative impacts on fish stocks because it can involve the bycatch of non-target species and it can put too much pressure on fish stocks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/blog/oceans/purse-seining-when-fishing-methods-go-bad-20100518|title=Overfishing - emptying our seas - Greenpeace UK|author=|date=|website=greenpeace.org.uk|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref>
{{multiple image | align = left | direction = horizontal | header = | header_align = center | image1 = Purse seine illustration, Historic American Engineering Record.png | width1 = 110 | alt1 = | caption1 = <center>Purse seine boat encircling a school of fish</center> | image2 = Chilean purse seine.jpg | width2 = 191 | alt2 = | caption2 = <center>A [[Shoaling and schooling|school]] of about 400 tons of [[jack mackerel]] encircled by a Chilean purse seiner</center> }}
